  "prompt": "How many colors and hues are distinguishable to the human eye?",
  "response": "The human eye is capable of distinguishing around 10 million different colors. This ability is due to the presence of three types of cone cells in the retina, each sensitive to different wavelengths of light\u2014commonly referred to as the short (S), medium (M), and long (L) wavelength cones. These cones allow the human visual system to perceive a wide spectrum of colors through various combinations of red, green, and blue light. \n\nWhen referring to hues, which are aspects of color related to the position of the color on the color spectrum (such as red, blue, and green), the human eye can perceive hundreds to perhaps a few thousand distinct hues. This perception is further influenced by factors such as lighting conditions, context, and individual vision differences.",
